<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-640-986 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 640 986.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 15 1991 n637 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The business of technology: compress this. (data compression)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rappaport, Andy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Used in small amounts, silicon is cheaper than metal.andP;  For thisreason many products are being 'demassified' by replacingmechanical parts with electronic parts.andP;  The same idea applies todata compression techniques, which have been popularized inconjunction with multimedia and the transmission of full-motionvideo.andP;  Silicon, when used in data compression applications, canbe used to expand the storage capacity of expensive magnetic andoptical drives significantly.andP;  For instance, a small investment insilicon that compresses data two to one is much more costeffective than having to double the size of a disk drive.andP;  Datacompression techniques do have a tradeoff in terms of accesstimes, but the reward of massively increased storage space makesit worthwhile.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data CompressionNew TechniqueOutlookEfficiencyIntegrated CircuitsStorage CapacityAccess Time.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>